Dynamic modedynamicmode operation in a liquid environment is more difficult than in air, because of significant damping of the cantilever oscillation due to the high viscosity of the surrounding media (Fig. 15.3Q-(quality) factorf). Significant damping results in a low quality factor Q of the oscillation, and thus the resonance frequency shift is difficult to track with high resolution. The quality factor is defined as 15.6Q=2Δff0.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Q=2\frac{\Updelta f}{f_{0}}\;.$$\end{document} Whereas in air the resonance frequency can easily be determined with a resolution of below 1 Hz, only a frequency resolution of about 20 Hz is expected for measurements in liquid environments.

